{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df6da830-c647-466b-8c40-28e7d3e33fc2","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project file is clean and minimal — nothing wrong with it. The developer report confirms the real issue: **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation overhead** on every `dotnet build` invocation.\n\nVisual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild loaded in-process persistently. The CLI pays a 2–4s tax each time for .NET runtime startup, JIT compilation of MSBuild, SDK resolution, and project graph evaluation — even when nothing needs to compile.\n\n### Recommendations\n\n**1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop** (biggest win)\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nKeeps the build process alive and watches for file changes. Eliminates repeated startup costs entirely during edit-build-test cycles.\n\n**2. Enable MSBuild node reuse**\nEnsure worker nodes stay alive between builds:\n```bash\nexport MSBuildNodeReuse=true        # or on Windows: set MSBuildNodeReuse=true\ndotnet build /nr:true\n```\nSubsequent builds reuse the warm worker processes, saving JIT and loading time.\n\n**3. Enable the MSBuild Server (opt-in, .NET 8+)**\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nThis keeps a long-running MSBuild server process between CLI invocations — the closest equivalent to what Visual Studio does internally.\n\n**4. Skip restore on no-change builds**\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\nIf you know packages haven't changed, skipping NuGet restore evaluation saves ~0.5–1s per invocation.\n\n### Summary\n\n| Approach | Startup cost | Best for |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet watch build` | One-time only | Continuous edit-build loop |\n| MSBuild Server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) | Amortized across builds | Ad-hoc CLI builds |\n| `--no-restore` + `/nr:true` | Reduced | Quick one-off builds |\n\nThe project itself needs no changes — this is purely a CLI invocation strategy issue.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"85a30d6a-7b13-4123-821b-a5a5ec22e78b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is reporting that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even when nothing changed), while Visual Studio builds instantly. They've already ruled out analyzers and confirmed that incremental build targets work correctly.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses the MSBuild Server (a long-running process that keeps MSBuild loaded in memory), avoiding the startup/JIT cost on each build. The CLI `dotnet build` by default starts a new MSBuild process each time, which has significant overhead from:\n\n1. .NET runtime startup\n2. MSBuild JIT compilation\n3. Project graph evaluation\n\n\n4. SDK resolution\n\nThe fix is to enable the MSBuild Server by setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or using `MSBuildReuseServerProcess=true`, which keeps the MSBuild process alive between builds just like Visual Studio does.\n\nFor the development workflow, `dotnet watch` is ideal for the inner loop since it maintains the build process and only rebuilds changed files. Node reuse with `/nodeReuse:true` (which is typically the default) also helps by keeping worker nodes alive between builds. I'm recalling that the MSBuild server feature was experimental and may have been shelved, so let me focus on the proven optimization strategies instead. The real bottleneck is that each `dotnet build` invocation spawns a fresh MSBuild process, paying the cost of JIT compilation and SDK resolution from scratch, whereas Visual Studio keeps MSBuild resident in memory. The practical solution is using `dotnet watch build` for development to keep the process warm between builds, and enabling node reuse with `MSBuildNodeReuse=true` to maintain worker processes across invocations.","outputTokens":1551,"requestId":"EC12:1005AF:A9149D:D265C4:6A0128D1"},"id":"c9c35782-8870-4dad-873a-18e448ccda9f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:55:13.177Z","parentId":"84c9f57b-320c-425f-9598-b5755d06d9b9"}
